===Interval act===
{{Further|Riverdance}}
It was confirmed on 22 March 2015 that the interval act for Eurovision Song Contest's Greatest Hits would be [[Riverdance]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Granger|first1=Anthony|title=Eurovision’s Greatest Hits: Riverdance to perform|url=http://eurovoix.com/2015/03/22/eurovisions-greatest-hits-riverdance-to-perform/|website=Eurovoix|accessdate=23 March 2015|date=22 March 2015}}</ref> The [[Theatre|theatrical]] show consisting mainly of [[Folk music of Ireland|traditional Irish music]] and [[Irish dance|dance]], and featured Irish dancing champions [[Jean Butler]] and [[Michael Flatley]], with a score composed by [[Limerick]] native [[Bill Whelan]], originated as an interval performance during the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1994]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Riverdance unveiled|url=http://www.rte.ie/archives/exhibitions/681-history-of-rte/707-rte-1990s/321057-eurovision-song-contest-1994/|website=RTÉ|accessdate=23 March 2015|date=30 April 1994}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Eurovision Song Contest 1994|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/by-year/contest?event=309|website=eurovision.tv|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|accessdate=23 March 2015}}</ref>

===Performances===
Fifteen Eurovision acts from thirteen countries participated in the anniversary concert.<ref name="Recording">{{cite web|last1=Storvik-Green|first1=Simon|title=Tonight: Recording of Eurovision's Greatest Hits|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/news?id=tonight_recording_of_eurovisions_greatest_hits_from_london|website=eurovision.tv|publisher=European Broadcasting Union|accessdate=1 April 2015|date=31 March 2015}}</ref> Although there were originally fourteen acts confirmed by the BBC, it was later announced on 5 March 2015 that {{Esccnty|Norway}}'s [[Bobbysocks]] would join the line-up increasing the total to fifteen.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Granger|first1=Anthony|title=ESC’s Greatest Hits: Bobbysocks to perform|url=http://eurovoix.com/2015/03/05/escs-greatest-hits-bobbysocks-to-perform/|website=Eurovoix|accessdate=5 March 2015|date=5 March 2015}}</ref> [[Video montage]]s were shown prior to each entry, showing footage for that particular year's contest, ending with Eurovision Song Contest footage for the entry that was about to perform on stage.<ref name=Eurovision60>{{Cite episode |title=Eurovision Song Contest's Greatest Hits |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02llhdd |accessdate=3 April 2015 |series=Eurovision Song Contest |serieslink=Eurovision Song Contest |first1=Graham |last1=Norton |first2=Petra |last2=Mede |network=[[British Broadcasting Corporation]] |station=[[BBC One]] |location=[[London]] |date=3 April 2015}}</ref>

