===Reprise performance===
A medley of some of the [[Eurovision Song Contest]]'s greatest hits were performed in English by all of the participating artists, as a reprise act at the close of the show, including: [[Anne-Marie David]] singing {{Esccnty|Israel}}'s winning entry of the [[Eurovision Song Contest 1979]], "[[Hallelujah (Gali Atari and Milk & Honey song)|Hallelujah]]". Swedish trio, [[Herreys]], sang "[[Nel blu dipinto di blu]]", which finished in third place at the {{Escyr|1958|1958 Eurovision}} for {{Esccnty|Italy}}'s [[Domenico Modugno]]. [[Bucks Fizz (band)|Bucks Fizz]]'s "[[Making Your Mind Up]]", the winning entry for {{Esccnty|United Kingdom}} in {{Escyr|1981}}, was performed by [[Bobbysocks!|Bobbysocks]]. The reprise concluded with Concita Wurst and Dana International leading all of the remaining performers (except Loreen) back on stage to sing [[ABBA]]'s [[Eurovision Song Contest 1974]] winning entry, "[[Waterloo (ABBA song)|Waterloo]]".<ref name=Eurovision60/>

==International broadcasting==
As the anniversary concert show was not [[live television|broadcast live]], the participating national broadcasters were able to broadcast the show on a date and channel that was convenient for their [[Broadcast programming|broadcasting schedules]].  Some broadcasters – such as Austria and Sweden – recorded additional links and interviews in London for their viewers and these were used as previews for the main show.<ref name="Broadcasting Schedule">{{cite web|title=Eurovision's Greatest Hits – Ticket FAQ|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/3Lk6TzSmghJSbSgsR27P29q/eurovisions-greatest-hits-ticket-faq|website=BBC|accessdate=5 February 2015|date=5 February 2015|quote=When will the show be broadcast in the UK / my country?}}</ref>

