{{Infobox play | name =The King's Speech | image = | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = | writer = [[David Seidler]] | chorus = | characters = | mute = | setting = | premiere = 2012 | place = [[Yvonne Arnaud Theatre]] | orig_lang = English | series = | subject = Biographical | genre = Drama | website = http://thekingsspeechonbroadway.com/site/ }}
'''''The King's Speech''''' is a 2012 [[Play (theatre)|play]] written by David Seidler and based on the [[83rd Academy Awards|2010]] [[Academy Award]]-winning [[The King's Speech|film of the same name]]. The play was staged at the [[Wyndham's Theatre]] on London's West End and opened on March 27th, 2012 and closed on May 12th, 2012.<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-17783302 King's Speech to close] accessed 11/5/2016</ref>
==Production history== The story of how King [[George VI]] overcame his fear of public speaking through the help of Australian speech therapist [[Lionel Logue]] was first researched by David Seidler in the 1970s. He had originally conceived the piece as a stage play, and contacted Valentine Logue, Lionel's son, and was able to gather information about the story. Valentine Logue asked Seidler to contact the [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Mother]] and ask her for approval of the story being publicized. The Queen responded she did not want the story told until after she died. The Queen Mother died in 2002, and it wasn't until 2005 that Seidler began working on the story again. It was instead conceived as film. The film version of ''The King's Speech'', that starred [[Colin Firth]] as King George and [[Geoffrey Rush]] as Lionel Logue, was a critical success and won several Oscars including Best Picture, Best Actor, and Best Supporting Actor. The success of the film encouraged producers to bring the story to the stage as originally intended.<ref>[http://www.playbill.com/article/the-kings-speech-to-transfer-to-west-ends-wyndhams-theatre-in-march-com-187594 King's Speech to transfer to West End] accessed 11/5/2016</ref>
The play made its World Premiere in February 2012 at the [[Yvonne Arnaud Theatre]]. It then went on a short tour in the UK and then premiered at the Wyndham's Theatre on the West End.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-news/9088425/The-Kings-Speech-to-transfer-to-West-End.html King's Speech to transfer] accessed 11/6/2016</ref>
In 2015, the play was staged at the [[Birmingham Repertory Theatre]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-reviews/11444450/The-Kings-Speech-Birmingham-Repertory-Theatre-review-dogged-persistence-pays-off.html King's Speech at Birmingham Rep] accessed 11/6/2016</ref> In 2016, the play was staged in Germany at the [[Rheinisches Landestheater Neuss|Neuss RLT]] Theatre.<ref>[http://www.rp-online.de/nrw/staedte/neuss/king-s-speech-ist-fuer-die-buehne-geschrieben-aid-1.5676725 Neuss King's Speech] accessed 11/6/2016</ref>
